          ],
          "contentBlocks": [
            {
              "blockId": "cb-c1",
              "type": "text",
              "content": "A <span class='glossary-link' data-term='confounder'>confounder</span> is most dangerous when it's something everyone overlooks because it feels like background. The discipline is to ask, for any claimed cause, 'what kind of person or place ends up in each group, and why?'"
            },
            {
              "blockId": "cb-c2",
              "type": "video",
              "url": "",
              "captionOrTranscript": "A short screencast walks through the Berkeley admissions paradox, where aggregate data suggested bias against women but department-level data reversed the picture once you accounted for which programs each group applied to."
            }
          ],
          "interactionSequence": [
            {
              "interactionId": "int-rank-1",
              "interactionType": "drag-drop",
              "prompt": "Rank these four explanations for 'students who own laptops score higher' from MOST to LEAST likely to be the real driver.",
              "required": true,
              "responseFormat": "ranking",
              "revealCondition": "after-attempt",
              "options": [
                "Family income (buys laptops AND tutoring, books, stability)",
                "The laptop itself improving learning",
                "Pure coincidence in this sample",
                "Higher scores cause laptop ownership"
              ],
              "correctIndex": 0,
              "correctOrder": [
                0,
                1,
                3,
                2
              ],
              "feedback": {
                "type": "elaborative",
                "elaborativeFeedback": "Income is the textbook confounder here: it independently raises both laptop ownership and test scores, so the laptop-score link can be almost entirely spurious. The laptop may add a little, but attributing the whole gap to it ignores who can afford one in the first place."
              }
            },
            {
              "interactionId": "int-conf-1",
              "interactionType": "scenario-analysis",
              "prompt": "A hospital reports that patients treated in its newest wing have higher death rates than those in the old wing. An administrator wants to close the new wing. What's the most likely confounder, and what does it imply?",
              "required": true,
              "responseFormat": "short-answer",
              "revealCondition": "after-response",
              "feedback": {
                "type": "elaborative",
                "elaborativeFeedback": "The new wing is almost certainly where the sickest patients are sent — the ICU-grade equipment lives there. Severity of illness is the confounder: it drives both <em>which wing</em> and <em>death rate</em>. Closing the wing would be exactly backwards; the higher raw death rate may reflect harder cases, not worse care."
              },
              "confidencePrompt": {
                "enabled": true,
                "scaleMin": 1,
